<br>
Ok.  Imagine you are in a nasty dungeon.  You are in combat with a mob, with your 20 melee all on the same side and a river of lava behind that mob.<br>
Now, for those not familiar with “pushing”, I’ll first explain that. (for the learning-impaired).<br>
Melee classes, when they hit a mob 30 times in a mere second or 2, can PUSH it back due to sheer number of hits connecting.  Put several high damage dealing melees together, and you can push that mob across a room.  Add in several nukers, and that mob will be up against that wall 40 feet away before you know it.  Now, this tactic is great for mobs that complete heal, since moving while casting interrupts spells.  <br>
HOWEVER, when you have a situation like that above, then pushing the mob into the river is a BAD IDEA.<br>
At this point, you will usually either see “SWITCH SIDES” in shout, or “BACK OFF”.<br>
I tell you, if I had a copper for every time I saw Back Off shouted, and saw at least 2 or 3 people still happily swinging away at ubermob_01, then I'd be rich enough to buy Maldan as my wardrobe bitch.<br>
People, it’s NOT THAT HARD.  Back off means simply that, BACK THE FUCK OFF.  There is no secret plan going on.  It’s not a joke or a means of trying to “fool you” into backing off so group 4 can get the xp.<br>
It means back off because BAD SHIT will happen if you continue attacking.<br>
And for those wondering, “switch sides” means you go on the exact opposite side and do the exact same thing, pushing the mob back the other way.  (as Sly mentioned in the part1 post, use strafe if you have to ... I could care less how the hell you do it, just get behind that friggin mob!)<br>
Switch sides does NOT mean 2 people get on the other side, while the other 30 melees stay on the original side and push the mob into the lava.... and then stare at the lava with a complete brainfart look on their face.<br>
These people need to die, or spend 2 hours alone in a room with Kelarniv...either way, they need help.<br>
<br>
Now, for the combat positioning part, I’ll tell you once again...IT’S NOT THAT HARD.<br>
So, for those “challenged” people, here’s some more comments for you :<br>
1 - the rogue.  This poor bastard has to sit on the other side of a spite golem trying to stab it in the gizzard while 80 melee are constantly pushing it into the wall.  Umm...yeah, hi, remember the little 3 footer that stabs for 500s?  Yeah, VERY important not to pin a mob in a corner if there is NO need for it.  This is why we use a term called &quot;surround the mob&quot;.<br>
2 - choose your position.  For those that haven't figured it out yet, aggro is sometimes determined solely by RANGE.  So those in a mob's face with a little dagger are gonna get smacked down before a warrior with a 2hander standing 3 feet away will.  Also, I've heard time and time again that rangers and rogues can tank.  This annoys the shit out of me.  Yes, we can..if need be...but why the fuck would we want to?  Rogues do their major damage from behind.  They CANNOT backstab from the front for those dipshits that haven't figured this out.  Rangers also get beaten down as main tank because of riposte damage.  For those that have ever dueled a ranger, you'll know that we don't hit for 200 dmg once every 10 seconds.  Instead, we hit for up to 80s (at my lvl anyways) about 100000 times per second (slight exaggeration, but I need to for some).  If you count a mob's damage to us, and THEN add on the riposte damage, this is why ranger's die tanking.  SO, then next time someone makes me tank in Sebilis, and then complains about the mana cost of heals, GET A GODDAMN CLUE.  YOU try tanking a mob that ripostes and beats the living shit out of you simply by counterattacks!  This is why rogues and rangers at higher levels usually attack from BEHIND the target..../boggle<br>
3 - blah, nm...I won't even start on the main tanks with 2handers / no haste gear above lvl50.  If you haven't figured it out by now, nothing I can say will help you.<br>
<br>
<br>
Hrmm...well, that’s about it for this lesson.<br>
